<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="1440" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="16.[160,1155,1619,1714]" box="[160,300,1619,1645]" pageId="16" pageNumber="1440">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,300,1619,1645]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="1440">Distribution</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[160,1155,1619,1714]" pageId="16" pageNumber="1440">
This is the first record from 
<collectingCountry box="[454,594,1654,1679]" name="Saudi Arabia" pageId="16" pageNumber="1440">Saudi Arabia</collectingCountry>
. The species was described from 
<collectingCountry box="[951,1027,1654,1679]" name="Austria" pageId="16" pageNumber="1440">Austria</collectingCountry>
and further recorded from 
<collectingCountry box="[325,404,1689,1714]" name="Algeria" pageId="16" pageNumber="1440">Algeria</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[414,490,1689,1714]" name="Tunisia" pageId="16" pageNumber="1440">Tunisia</collectingCountry>
and Europe (widespread) (
<bibRefCitation author="Kechev M" box="[787,928,1689,1714]" pageId="16" pageNumber="1440" pagination="53 - 57" refId="ref13110" refString="Kechev M. 2017. New records of long-legged flies (Diptera: Dolichopodidae) from Greece. Silva Balcanica. 10 (1): 53 - 57." type="journal article" year="2017">Kechev 2017</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Grichanov IYa" box="[941,1125,1689,1714]" pageId="16" pageNumber="1440" pagination="1 - 563" refId="ref12513" refString="Grichanov IYa. 2017 a. Alphabetic list of generic and specific names of predatory flies of the epifamily Dolichopodoidae (Diptera). 2 nd ed. St. Petersburg: VIZR (Plant Protection News Suppl. 23); p. 1 - 563." type="journal article" year="2017">Grichanov 2017a</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="1441" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="17.[160,1155,142,237]" pageId="17" pageNumber="1441">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,268,142,168]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1441">Remarks.</emphasis>
The biology is unknown. This species was found in a range of wetlands including fens, damp wood and coastal locations; larvae may be semi-aquatic predators (
<bibRefCitation author="Falk SJ &amp; Crossley R" box="[166,424,212,237]" pageId="17" pageNumber="1441" pagination="1 - 134" refId="ref12210" refString="Falk SJ, Crossley R. 2005. A review of the scarce and threatened flies of Great Britain. Part 3: Empidoidea. Species Status. 3: 1 - 134. (Peterborough: Joint Nature Conservation Committee)." type="journal article" year="2005">Falk and Crossley 2005</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
